==Korean==
===Noun===
'''머루''' (''meoru'')
#[[wild]] [[grape]], (''obsolete'') [[grape]] 

====Alternative spellings====
*멀위 (''meorWi'') (''obsolete'')
*멀구 (''meolgu'') (''dialect'') 

====Synonyms====
*[[산]]머루 (''san-'') [[wild]] [[grape]]
*[[산]]포도 (''san-podo'') [[wild]] [[grape]]
*[[포도]] ([[葡萄]], ''podo'') [[grape]] cf. French '''grappe de raisin''' "bunch of grapes", French [[raisin]] "grape" from Latin [[racemus]] "bunch of grapes"

====Derived terms====
*[[산]]머루  (''san-'') [[wild grape]]
*[[왕]]머루  (''wang-'') [[Amur grape]]

====Related terms====
*[[송이]] (''songI'') (''fruit'') [[bunch]], [[cluster]] 
*[[덤불]] (''deombul'') [[bush]], [[shrub]], [[thicket]] 
*[[덩굴]](''deonggul'') [[vine]] 

====See also====
*[[오디]] (''odi'') [[mulberry]] cf. Italian '''[[mora]]''' 
*[[검은딸기]] (''geomEun-ttalgi'') [[blackberry]] cf. Italian '''[[mora]]''' 
*[[나무딸기]] (''namu-ttalgi'') [[raspberry]]
*[[산딸기]] (''san-ttalgi'') [[raspberry]], [[wild]] [[berry]]
{{trans-top|Notes}}
Italian [[mora]], for example, refers to [[mulberry]] and [[blackberry]], both of which are very different in nature but easily confused in appearance. Historically, either berries may have been also confused with grapes, especially in the wilderness.     
{{bottom}}

